**Offer Him** following things:-

* Vaishnavs have following qualities:-

* Offer him by not getting attached to the fruits of your action by **neither overjoying nor lamenting.**  
* **Offer him your penance** of a **mindset free of lust, anger and fear and not desiring fruits of action performed. Neither have a sense of proprietorship.**

## Chapter 2

Never was there a time when I did not exist, nor you, nor all these kings; nor in the future shall any of us cease to be.(2.12)  
\-\> Individuality of soul is maintained. We never become one. Becoming one is seen as spiritual suicide.  
\-\>Arjuna, the wise man to whom pain and pleasure are alike, and who is not tormented by these contacts, becomes eligible for immortality. (2.15)

Q1. What is the state of the soul before and after the birth?  
Arjuna, before birth,beings souls are not manifest to our human senses; on death they return to the unmanifest again. They are manifest only in the interim between birth and death. What occasion, then, for lamentation? (2.28) 

Q2. **Importance of Duty**

(3.8)  
Now, if you refuse to fight this righteous war, then, shirking your duty and losing your reputation, you will incur sin.(2.33)

Treating alike victory and defeat, gain and loss, pleasure and pain, get ready for the battle; fighting thus you will not incur sin.(2.38)

Hitherto, I have explained to you Sānkhya Yog, or analytic knowledge regarding the nature of the soul. Now listen, O Parth, as I reveal Buddhi Yog, or the Yog of Intellect. When you work with such understanding, you will be freed from the bondage of karma.(2.39)  
In chapter 2 Buddhi yog is the same as karma yog.

**VEDAS**  
Arjuna, those who are full of worldly desires and devoted to the letter of the Vedas, who look upon heaven, as the supreme goal and argue that there is nothing beyond heaven are unwise. They utter flowery speech recommending many rituals of various kinds for the attainment of pleasure and power with rebirth as their fruit. Those whose minds are carried away by such words, and who are deeply attached to pleasures and worldly power, cannot attain the determinate intellect concentrated on God. (2.42-44)

Arjuna, the Vedas thus deal with the evolutes of the three Gunas (modes of Prakæti), viz., worldly enjoyments and the means of attaining such enjoyments; be thou indifferent to these enjoyments and their means, **rising above pairs of opposites like pleasure and pain** etc., **established in** the Eternal Existence **(God)**, absolutely **unconcerned about the fulfilment of wants** and the preservation of what has been already attained, and self-controlled. (45)

You have a right to perform your prescribed duties, but you are not entitled to the fruits of your actions. Never consider yourself to be the cause of the results(good or bad) of your activities, **nor be attached to inaction**.(2.47)

**PRESCRIBED DUTY**  
Be **steadfast/equipoised(yoga-stha**ḥ) in the performance of your duty, O Arjun, abandoning attachment to success and failure. Such equanimity is called Yog.(2.48,3.8)  
**SHEDS PAST KARMAS \+ Increase the quality of work**  
Endowed with equanimity, **one sheds in this life both good and evil.** Therefore, strive for the practice of this Yoga of equanimity. **Skill in action lies in the practice of this Yoga**. (2.50)   
**SACRIFICE OF FRUITS OF ACTION SHOWS DETACHMENT.**  
For, wise men possessing equipoised mind, **renouncing the fruit of actions** and **freed from the shackles of birth**, attain the blissful supreme state. (2.51)   
**CONFUSION**  
When your intellect, confused by hearing conflicting statements, will rest steady and undistracted in meditation on God, you will then attain Yoga (everlasting union with God). (2.53)

**Arjuna said : Krsna, what is the definition (mark) of a God-realised soul, stable of mind and established in Samådhi (perfect tranquillity of mind)? How does the man of stable mind speak, how does he sit, how does he walk?(2.54)**  
**CHARACTERISTICS OF SELF REALISED SOUL (NO ATTACHMENT WITH ANYONE IN THIS MATERIAL WORLD \- ILLUSION/TEMPORARY)**  
›r∂ Bhagavån said: Arjuna, when one thoroughly **casts off all cravings of the mind**, and is **satisfied in the Self** through the joy of the Self, he is then called stable of mind.(2.55)

The sage, whose mind remains unperturbed amid sorrows, whose **thirst for pleasures has altogether disappeared**, and who is **free from desire, fear and anger**, is called stable of mind.(2.56)

He who is **unattached to everything**, and on meeting with **good and evil, neither rejoices nor recoils**, his mind is stable and is firmly fixed in perfect knowledge. (2.57)

When, like a tortoise, that draws in its limbs from all directions, he **withdraws all his senses from the sense-objects**, his mind becomes steady.(2.58)

Aspirants may restrain the senses from their objects of enjoyment, but the taste for the sense objects remains. However, **even this taste ceases** for those who realises the Supreme.(2.59)  
Though the embodied soul may be restricted from sense enjoyment, the taste for sense object remains. But ceasing such engagements by experiencing a **higher taste**, he is fixed in consciousness.(2.59 by SP)

Turbulent by nature, the senses (not free from attachment) even of a wise man, who is practising self-control, forcibly carry away his mind, Arjuna.(60)   
**FIXING CONSCIOUSNESS ON KRISHNA**  
Therefore, having controlled all the senses and concentrating his mind, he should sit for meditation, **devoting himself heart and soul to Me**. For, he whose **senses are under his control**, is known to have a stable mind.(2.61)  
SP \- One who restrains his senses, keeping them under full control, and fixes his consciousness upon Me, is known as a man of steady intelligence. (2.61).  
**CONTROLLING MIND WHILE PERFORMING MATERIALISTIC ACTIVITIES**  
**But one who controls the mind, and is free from attachment and aversion, even while using the objects of the senses(viṣhayān), attains the Grace of God.(2.64)**

As the waters of different rivers enter the ocean, which, though full on all sides, remains undisturbed; likewise, he, in whom all enjoyments merge themselves without causing disturbance, attains peace; not he who hankers after such enjoyments.(2.70)  
**GOD CONSCIOUSNESS EVEN AT LAST MOMENT.**  
Arjuna, such is the state of the God-realised soul; having reached this state, he overcomes delusion(bewilderedness). **And established in this state, even at the last moment(at the time of death)**, he attains Brahmic Bliss/liberation from Maya/free from cycle of birth and death and enters into Kingdom of God. (2.72)

---

SUMMARY STEPS:

* Anything that is not spiritual or anything not centred on Krishna is material.  
* You should **not get attached to ANYTHING(2.57).** Everything is  temporary and an ILLUSION. But it does not mean that you should get attached to inaction(2.47,2.33,2.48). You should perform the prescribed duty religiously **with your mind fixed on Krishna.(2.61).**  
* Detachment does not mean renouncement of your duties and material life. You can perform Karma Yoga even during the process of using the materialistic objects(2.64) but not getting attached to it with consciousness fixed on Krishna.  
* Perform your prescribed duty with a mindset of having **equipoised** and **steadfast(**Because God is not responsible for the fruits of action performed, it is Gunas or Prakriti which is alone responsible(5.14)**)**(2.48), not desiring the fruits of action performed.  
* Do your work keeping Krishna at centre, for **His satisfaction and renounce the fruits of the action unto Him(2.51,5.10,5.12)-\>(**be careful not to have sense of proprietorship**) by not showing your attachment/enjoyment towards the rewards or not showing your grief even after not getting it.(2.57)**  
* Spread love, happiness, treat others well but you should not have a thirst of desires/pleasures. You should be free from **DESIRE(lust), FEAR and ANGER**.(2.56)  
* All these qualities will make your mind free of miseries and full of peace(2.70) also it sheds past karma in this life itself(2.50), fixed and of firm intellect which is capable of handling worst possible situation calmly and it will make your soul eligible for ब्रह्मनिर्वाण-2.72,5.25.  
* **See Krishna everywhere**(6.29,6.30,18.61)

## Chapter 3

He who outwardly restraining the organs of sense and action, sits **mentally dwelling on the objects of senses**, that man of deluded intellect is called a hypocrite/pretender. (3.6) 

On the other hand, he who controls the organs of sense and action **by the power of his will**, and remaining unattached, undertakes the Karma Yoga of selfless Action through those organs, Arjuna, he excels. (3.7)

Therefore, do your **prescribed duty**; for action is superior to inaction. Desisting from action, you cannot even maintain your body. (3.8)

Man is bound by his own action except when it is performed **for the sake of sacrifice**. Therefore, Arjuna, do you efficiently perform your **duty,** free from attachment, for the sake of sacrifice **alone**. (3.9)   
Other translation:-  
Work must be done as a yajna to the Supreme Lord; otherwise, work causes bondage in this material world. Therefore, O son of Kunti, for the **satisfaction of God, perform your prescribed duties**, without being attached to the results.(3.9)

Sacrifice \= Satisfaction.

\-\>Sacrifice is done to satisfy Vishnu, so you should do all your work for the satisfaction of the lord(God should say ‘Now enough\!’). Any other work in this material world will cause bondage.

In the beginning of creation, Brahma created humankind along with duties, and said, “Prosper in the performance of these *yajñas* (sacrifices), for they shall bestow upon you all you wish to achieve”.By your sacrifices, the celestial gods will be pleased, and by cooperation between humans and the celestial gods, great prosperity will reign for all.Fostered by sacrifice, the gods will surely bestow on you unasked all the desired enjoyments. He **who enjoys the gifts bestowed by them without offering anything to them in return, is undoubtedly a thief**.The virtuous who partake of what is **left over after sacrifice**, are absolved of all sins. Those sinful ones who **cook** for the sake of nourishing their bodies alone, partake of sin only. (3.10-3.13)

All beings are evolved from food; production of food is dependent on rain; rain ensues from sacrifice, and sacrifice is rooted in prescribed action. Know that prescribed action has its origin in the Vedas, and the **Vedas proceed directly  from God**; hence the all-pervading Infinite is always present in sacrifice. (3.14-3.15)  
Arjuna, he who does not follow the wheel of creation thus set going in this world i.e., does not perform his duties, leads a sinful and sensual life, he lives in vain.(3.16)  
He, however, who takes delight in the Self alone and is gratified with the Self, and is contented in the Self, **has no duty**. (3.17).  
(Such a person does not have any obligations to the Vedic injunctions. Such a Krsna conscious person is no longer interested in material activities. By nature’s law this human form of life is specially meant for self-realisation, in either of the three ways-namely Karma yoga, jnana-yoga or bhakti yoga. There is no necessity of rigidly following the performances of the prescribed yajnas for the transcendentalists who are above vice and virtue;but those who are engaged in sense gratification require purification by the above mentioned cycle of yajna performances. The yajna system is planned in such a way that sensory conscious persons may satisfy their desires without becoming entangled in the reaction of sense-gratifactory work).

In this world that **great** soul has nothing to gain by action nor by abstaining from action; nor has he **selfish dependence** of any kind on any creature.(3.18)  
Self realised person **does not have any purpose to fulfil in the discharge of his duties**, **nor has he reason not to perform such work**. Nor has he need to depend on any other living being.(3.18-SP)  
Therefore, go on **efficiently doing your duty** at all times without attachment. Doing work without attachment man attains the Supreme(**परमाप्नोति**). (3.19)

Kings such as Janaka attained perfection solely by performance of prescribed duties. Therefore, just for the **sake of educating the people** in general, you should perform your work. Whatever action a great man performs, common men follow. And whatever standards he sets by exemplary acts, all the world pursues.(3.20-3.21)  
As ignorant people perform their duties with attachment to the results, O scion of Bharat, so should the wise act without attachment, **for the sake of leading people on the right path( [*loka-saṅgraham*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/loka-sangraham)—for the welfare of the world)**.(3.25)

**WHO PERFORMS THE ACTION?**  
In fact all actions are being performed by the modes of Prakæti (Primordial Matter or the three modes of material nature). The fool, whose mind is deluded by egoism([*ahankāra-vimūḍha-ātmā*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/ahankara-vimudha-atma)), thinks: I am the doer.(3.27)

→Can also be understood that we are trapped in a simulation. We(souls) are not the doer. We think we are independent. But actually we are in control of our senses which causes the result of our activities and the simulation of spontaneous existence. We are the most loyal and faithful servants of our senses and we think that we are independent. Hence no one is independent in this world, it is therefore our choice whether we want to be dependent on our senses or on Krishna. Each and every action of ours is conducted under the three modes of material nature(goodness-sattva guna, passion-rajo guna and ignorance-tamo guna).

→From senior Vaishnav vaani, It is inferred that action done by Krishna conscious person is directly under the control of Krishna. But action of a non devotee is directly controlled by Prakriti which functions under Krishna’s direction.

→ Hence it is very important for us to know that the results of our actions are due to the combination of the 3 modes of material nature by which our body is made. But out of ignorance soul identifies with the body and becomes implicated as the doer of actions   
**ABOUT PERFORMING KARMA BEING ATTACHED TO RESULT.**  
O mighty-armed Arjuna\! But the knower of Truth understands the **divisions of qualities and functions**. He knows that the **qualities in the form of senses function amidst the objects of the senses**, and **he, as the Supreme Self,** is not affected by them. Thus knowing, he remains unattached.(3.28) {vivekavani.com}

Those who are completely deluded by the Guƒas (modes) of Prakæti remain attached to those Guƒas and actions; the **man of perfect Knowledge should not unsettle the mind of those ignorants of imperfect knowledge**. (3.29)  
(Because these duties are inferior due to the performer’s lack of knowledge. Those who are in the path of spiritual life should not agitate such materially engrossed persons. They falsely identify themselves with gross material consciousness and are full of material designations. Person who is too attached to bodily consciousness is called ‘manda’. They are always busy in material fields and for them spiritual realisation is a myth and so they are not interested. Such bewildered persons may be engaged in such primary moral principles of life as nonviolence and similar materially benevolent work. They cannot appreciate Krishna consciousness and therefore Lord advises us not to disturb them and better to prosecute one’s own spiritual activities silently- As with materialistic association may  come a seed of doubt. But the devotees of the Lord are more kind than the Lord because they understand the purpose of the Lord. Consequently they undertake all kinds of risks, even to the point of approaching ignorant men to try to engage them in the acts of Krsna consciousness, which are absolutely necessary for human being.)  
A wise man established in the Self should not unsettle the mind of the ignorant attached to action, but should get them to perform all their duties, duly performing his own duties. (3.26) 

**WITH WHAT MIND SHOULD WE DO OUR WORK?**  
Therefore, O Arjuna, surrendering/dedicating (as an offering) all works unto Me (*sannyasyā*), with your mind fixed on Me (*ādhyātma-chetasā*), without desires for profit(or fruit of action performed)([*nirāśhīḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/nirashih)), with no claims to proprietorship([*nirmamaḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/nirmamah)) and without free from any kind of mental agitation(or lethargy), fight. (3.30)

**KRISHNA GIVES ASSURANCE (only for person with faith and without envy)**  
Those persons who execute their duties according to My injunctions and who follow this teaching faithfully ( [*śhraddhā-vantaḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/shraddha-vantah)), without envy ([*anasūyantaḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/anasuyantah)) , become free from the bondage of fruitive actions ([*karmabhiḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/karmabhih)).

**FOR THOSE WHO HAVE NO FAITH IN KRISHNA**  
But those who, out of envy ([*abhyasūyantaḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/abhyasuyantah)), disregard these teachings and do not ([*na*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/na)) follow them regularly ([*anutiṣhṭhanti*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/anutishthanti)) are to be considered bereft of all knowledge([*sarva-jñāna*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/sarva-jnana)), befooled ([*vimūḍhān*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/vimudhan)), and ruined ([*naṣhṭān*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/nashtan)) in their endeavours for perfection. (3.32)  
He who lacks discrimination, is devoid of faith, and is at the same time possessed by doubt about the revealed scriptures, is lost to the spiritual path and does not attain God consciousness. For the doubting soul there is neither this world nor the world beyond, nor even happiness. (4.40)

**WHY A PERSON IS UNABLE TO BUILD FAITH?**  
All living creatures follow their tendencies; even the wise man acts according to the tendencies of his own nature. Of what use is any external restraint? (3.33)

There are principles to regulate (vyavasthitau) attachment and aversion pertaining to the senses and their objects.  
Attraction([*rāga*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/raga)) and repulsion([*dveṣhau*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/dveshau)) are rooted in all sense objects([*indriyasya arthe*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/indriyasya%20arthe)). Man should never allow himself to be swayed by them, because they are the two principal enemies([*paripanthinau*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/paripanthinau)) standing in the way of his self realisation. (3.34)

**Why a person do sinful activities (problem with mode of passion)?**  
**Arjun asked: Why is a person impelled to commit sinful acts, even unwillingly, as if by force, O descendent of Vrishni (Krishna)? (3.36)**  
The Supreme Lord said: It is lust ( [*kāmaḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/kamah)) alone, which is born of contact with the mode of passion ([*rajaḥ-guṇa*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/rajah-guna)), and later transformed into anger ([*krodhaḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/krodhah)). Know this as the sinful([*mahā-pāpmā*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/maha-papma)), all-devouring enemy ([*vairiṇam*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/vairinam)) in the world.(3.37)

As fire is covered by smoke, mirror by dust, and embryo by the amnion, so is knowledge covered by desire (when one in in mode of passion).(3.38)  
**DESIRE CANNOT BE SATISFIED.**  
And, Arjuna, Knowledge stands covered by this eternal enemy of the wise known as desire, which is insatiable like fire.(3.39)

**SENSE, MIND AND INTELLIGENCE**  
The senses ([*indriyāṇi*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/indriyani)), the mind ([*manaḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/manah)) and the intelligence ([*buddhiḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/buddhih)) are the sitting places of this lust. Through them lust or desire (from mode of passion) covers the real knowledge ([*jñānam*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/jnanam)) of the living entity and deludes the embodied soul.(3.40)

The senses are said to be greater than the body; but greater than the senses is the mind. Greater than the mind is the intellect; and what is greater than the intellect is He, the Self. (3.42)

Therefore, Arjuna, you must first control your senses, and then kill this evil thing(desire/lust which is the embodiment of sin ([*pāpmānam*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/papmanam))) which obstructs Jnåna/knowledge (Knowledge of Self as distinguished from the non Self) and Vijnåna/ Self realisation(Specific knowledge of the spirit soul’s constitutional position and his relationship with God).

Thus knowing the soul to be superior to the material intellect, O mighty armed Arjun, subdue the lower self (senses, mind, and intellect) by the higher self (strength of the soul), and kill this formidable enemy called lust. (3.43)

---

Summary Steps:-

* Try to control senses by power of will. As body\<senses\<mind\<intelligence\<Self(soul) (3.7, 3.42)  
* Do your action for the sake of sacrifice alone (3.9)  
* Eat the sacrificial food or thank God for his divine grace.(also done to remove bondage of eating for sense gratification).  
*  You should have nothing to gain by action nor should you abstain from action. Also you should not have self dependence on any other creature.(3.18)  
* We should not have a sense of doership. Therefore we should be grateful, we should not be proud of success and we should not become depressed by failures. (3.27)  
* We should know the difference between qualities and functions.(3.28)  
* Nature of the soul is to enjoy. But enjoying via desire/lust is where we commit mistakes. By doing this we get more entangled and we further worsen our situation.Because these desires cannot be satisfied(3.39). It is like eating samosas in Jaundice. These desires make our consciousness more attached to this illusion.  
* Work without bondage and mind absorbed in Krishna→how?  
* For the sake of sacrifice(4.23)  
* To satisfy the Supreme lord.  
* To set an example for the world.(3.20,21,35)

## Chapter 4

**ROOTS OF THIS TRANSCENDENTAL KNOWLEDGE**  
›r∂ Bhagavån said: I revealed this immortal Yoga to Vivasvån (Sun-god); Vivasvån conveyed it to Manu (his son); and Manu imparted it to (his son) Iksvåku.  
Thus transmitted in succession from father to son, Arjuna, this Yoga remained known to the Råjarsis (royal sages) by the chain of continuous tradition/**disciplic succession** (paramparā). Through a long lapse of time, this Yoga got lost to the world. (4.1-2)

\-\>This indicates that Bhagavad-gita is not a speculative treatise for insignificant mundane scholars but a standard book of knowledge from time immemorial. Krishna did not give this knowledge to any ordinary person. He selected the sun god because the sun is the king of all planets and controls all planets and is rotating under Krishna’s order (Ref. Brahma Samhita 5.52) 

\-\>It has existed in human society since Maharaj Iksvaku (2,005,000 years)  Given to Vivasvan at least 120,400,000 years ago  Again spoken to Arjuna 5000 years ago. Why? – Because original purpose was scattered by motives of unscrupulous commentators

**WHO CAN UNDERSTAND THIS DIVINE KNOWLEDGE**  
That very ancient science of the relationship with the Supreme is today told by Me to you because you are **My devotee** as well as **My friend** and can therefore understand the transcendental mystery of this science.(4.3)  
Other references on Qualifications Ref. 4.34, 4.39, 9.1, 18.67-68  
**ABOUT KRISHNA**  
The Personality of Godhead said: Many, many births both you and I have passed. **I can remember all of them**, but you cannot, O subduer of the enemy\!(4.5)  
Though **birthless** and **immortal** and the **Lord of all beings**, I incarnate (s[*ambhavāmi*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/sambhavami)) Myself through My own Yogamåyå (divine potency/internal energy \- [*ātma-māyayā*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/atma-mayaya)), keeping My nature (Prakæti) under control.(4.6)  
Whenever and wherever there is a decline in religious practice, O descendant of Bharata, and a predominant rise of irreligion – at that time I descend Myself.(4.7)  
To deliver the pious and to annihilate the miscreants, as well as to reestablish the principles of religion, I Myself appear, millennium after millennium.(4.8)

**DIFFERENCE BETWEEN KRISHNA AND CONDITIONED LIVING ENTITY**

![][image1]  
**PATH TO LIBERATION**  
One who knows the transcendental ([*divyam*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/divyam)) nature of My appearance ([*janma*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/janma)) and activities ([*karma*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/karma)) does not, upon leaving the body (*tyaktvā dehaṁ*), take his birth again(*punar janma*) in this material world, but attains My eternal abode (*mām eti*), O Arjuna. (4.9)  
Being freed from attachment, fear and anger, being fully absorbed in Me and taking refuge in Me, many, many persons in the past became purified by knowledge of Me – and thus they all attained transcendental love for Me ( [*mat-bhāvam*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/mat-bhavam)).(4.10)  
Arjuna, howsoever men seek Me (surrender/[*prapadyante*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/prapadyante)), even so do I respond to them; for all men follow My path in every way.(4.11)  
**DEMIGODS**  
In this world, those desiring success in material activities worship the celestial gods, since material rewards manifest quickly.(4.12)  
**4 DIVISIONS OF HUMAN SOCIETY**  
According to the three modes of material nature and the work associated with them, the four divisions of human society **are created by Me.** And although I am the creator of this system, you should know that I am yet the non-doer, being unchangeable. (4.13)  
**KARMA, AKARMA AND VIKARMA**  
**Even the intelligent are bewildered** in determining what is action and what is inaction. Now I shall explain to you what action is, knowing which you shall be liberated from all misfortune. (4.16)  
The intricacies of action are very hard to understand. Therefore one should know properly what action([*karmaṇaḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/karmanah)) is, what forbidden action([*vikarmaṇaḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/vikarmanah)) is and what inaction ([*akarmaṇaḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/akarmanah)) is. (4.17)

* Karma : Pious activity  
* Vikarma : Impious activity  
* Akarma : Spiritual activity (ABCDE)

**CHARACTERISTICS OF A KARMA YOGI**  
One who sees **inaction in action** and **action in inaction** is intelligent among men, and **he is in the transcendental position, although engaged in all sorts of activities**. (4.18)  
One is understood to be in full knowledge whose **every endeavour is devoid of desire for sense gratification**. He is said by sages to be a worker for whom the reactions of work have been burned up by the fire of perfect knowledge.(4.19)  
He, who, having **totally given up attachment to the fruits of their action,** **no longer depends on anything in the world**, and is **ever content, does nothing at all, though fully engaged in action**. (20)   
Such a man of understanding acts with mind and intelligence perfectly controlled, **gives up all sense of proprietorship over his possessions**. **They incur no sin even though performing actions by their body.**(4.21)  
The Karmayog∂, who is contented with whatever is got unsought, is **free from jealousy** and has transcended all pairs of opposites like joy and grief, and is **balanced in success and failure**, is not bound by his action. (4.22)  
All his actions get dissolved entirely, who is free from attachment and has **no identification with the body**; and **free from the feeling of mine**, whose **mind is established in the knowledge of Self** and **who works merely for the sake of sacrifice.** (4.23)  
**DIFFERENT TYPES OF SACRIFICES DONE BY PEOPLE**  
All these different types of sacrifice are approved by the Vedas, and all of them are born of different types of work. Knowing them as such, you will become liberated. (4.32)  
From shloka 4.25-4.29

* Some yogis perfectly worship demigods by offering different material sacrifices to them.(25)  
* While others perform sacrifice by offering the self by the Self itself in the fire of Brahma through the sacrifice known as the perception of identity(end their individual existence by merging into the existence of the Supreme ).(25)  
* Some sacrifice the hearing process and other senses in the fire of self control.(26)  
* Some(householders) sacrifice the objects of the senses(for example regulated sex life, meat-eating, intoxication) in the fire of senses. It is also a kind of yajna because the restricted householder sacrifices his general tendency towards sense gratification for higher transcendental life.(26)  
* Some sacrifice all the functions of their senses and the functions of the vital airs (Pråƒa) into the fire of Yoga in the shape of self-control, kindled by wisdom.(27)  
* Having accepted strict vows, some become enlightened by sacrificing their possessions, and others by performing severe austerities, by practising the yoga of eightfold mysticism, or by studying the Vedas to advance in transcendental knowledge.(28)  
* Some by pranayama(controlling the breathing process) and some others by curtailing the eating process.(29)

**WHY SACRIFICE IS IMPORTANT**  
O best of the Kuru dynasty, without sacrifice one can never live happily on this planet or in this life: what then of the next?(4.31)  
**RECOMMENDED WAY OF SACRIFICE**  
Arjuna, sacrifice through Knowledge is superior to sacrifice performed with material things. For all actions without exception culminate in Knowledge, O son of Kunt∂. (4.33)

**IMPORTANCE OF GURU**  
Understand the true nature of that Knowledge by approaching an illumined soul. If you prostrate at their feet, render them service, and question them with an open and guileless heart, those wise seers of Truth will instruct you in that Knowledge.(4.34)  
**EVEN FOR THE MOST SINFUL OF ALL SINNERS**  
Even if you are considered to be the most sinful of all sinners, when you are situated in the boat of transcendental knowledge you will be able to cross over the ocean of miseries. (4.36)  
**YOU WILL ACQUIRE THE KNOWLEDGE(TRUTH) FROM WITHIN**  
In this world there is no purifier as great as Knowledge; he who has attained purity of heart through prolonged practice of Karma Yoga (work in devotional consciousness to God without getting attached to the fruits of action, devoid of desire, ever content and having no sense of proprietorship), automatically sees the light of Truth in the self in course of time.(4.38)  
**FAITH IS IMPORTANT**  
A f**aithful** man who is dedicated to transcendental **knowledge** and who **subdues his senses**(संयतेन्द्रिय:) is eligible to achieve such knowledge, and having achieved it he quickly attains the supreme spiritual peace in the form of self realization.(4.39)

But ignorant and faithless persons who doubt the revealed scriptures do not attain God consciousness; they fall down. For the doubting soul there is happiness neither in this world nor in the next.(4.40)

Therefore, Arjuna slashing to pieces, with the sword of knowledge, this doubt in your heart, born of ignorance, establish yourself in Karmayoga in the shape of even-mindedness, and stand up for the fight. (4.42)  
**KARMA YOGA IN ONE SHLOKA**  
**One who acts in devotional service, renouncing the fruits of his actions, and whose doubts have been destroyed by transcendental knowledge, is situated factually in the self. Thus he is not bound by the reactions of work, O conqueror of riches**. (4.41)

## **Chapter 5**

**RENUNCIATION VS KARMA YOGA**  
The Supreme Lord said: Both the path of *karm sanyās* (renunciation of actions) and *karm yog* (working in devotion) lead to the supreme goal. But *karm yog* is superior to *karm sanyās*. (5.2)

* Here Karm sanyas is renunciation of fruitive activities which is not recommended. According to Srila Prabhupada, mere knowledge (that one is not this material body but a spirit soul) is not sufficient for liberation. One has to act in the status of spirit soul. Without Krishna consciousness mere renunciation of fruitive activities does not actually purify the heart of a conditioned soul.

**KARMA YOGA DEFINED AGAIN**  
One who neither hates nor desires the fruits of his activities is known to be always renounced. Such a person, free from all dualities, easily overcomes material bondage and is completely liberated, O mighty-armed Arjuna.(5.3)

Without Karmayoga, however, Sånkhyayoga i.e., renunciation of doership in relation to all activities of the mind, senses and body is difficult to accomplish; whereas the Karmayog∂, who keeps his mind fixed on God, reaches Brahma in no time, Arjuna. (5.6)

The Karmayog∂, who has fully conquered his mind and mastered his senses, whose heart is pure, and who has identified himself with the Self of all beings (viz., God), remains untainted, even though performing action. (5.7)

The Karmayog∂s perform action only with their **senses, mind, intellect and body** as well, without the feeling of mine in respect of them and shaking off attachment, only for the purpose of self-purification. (5.11) 

A person who neither rejoices upon achieving something pleasant nor laments upon obtaining something unpleasant, who is self-intelligent, who is un-bewildered, and who knows the science of God is already situated in transcendence.(5.20)

Such a liberated person is not attracted to material sense pleasure (but uses material objects and senses for purification) but is always in trance, enjoying the pleasure within. In this way the self-realised person enjoys unlimited happiness, for he concentrates/meditates on the Supreme.(5.21)

**FREE FROM LUST/DESIRE, ANGER , FEAR**

- For those *sanyāsīs*, who have broken out of anger and lust through constant effort, who have subdued their mind, and are self-realized, liberation from material existence is both here and hereafter.(5.26)  
- The sage, whose mind remains unperturbed amid sorrows, whose **thirst for pleasures has altogether disappeared**, and who is **free from desire, fear and anger**, is called stable of mind.(2.56)

**HOW TO CONTROL LUST, ANGER AND FEAR**  
Shutting out all external sense objects, keeping the eyes and vision concentrated between the two eyebrows, suspending the inward and outward breaths within the nostrils, and thus controlling the mind, senses and intelligence, the transcendentalist aiming at liberation becomes free from desire([*icchā*](https://vedabase.io/en/search/synonyms/?original=icch%C4%81) ), fear([*bhaya*](https://vedabase.io/en/search/synonyms/?original=bhaya)) and anger([*krodhaḥ*](https://vedabase.io/en/search/synonyms/?original=krodha%E1%B8%A5) ). One who is **always([*sadā*](https://vedabase.io/en/search/synonyms/?original=sad%C4%81) )** in this state is certainly liberated([*muktaḥ*](https://vedabase.io/en/search/synonyms/?original=mukta%E1%B8%A5)).(5.27-28)

* Here Krishna is explaining about ashtanga yoga. By practising this yoga one is able to gain control over the senses, refrain from outward sense objects, and thus prepare oneself for liberation. This yoga helps one become free from all kinds of fear and anger and thus feel the presence of the Supersoul in the transcendental situation.  
* It as an **impractical path**; and therefore one should reject it in favour of bhakti-yoga or Krishna consciousness. A Krishna conscious person however being always engaged in devotional service does not risk losing his senses to some other engagement. This is better way of controlling the senses than by ashtanga yoga.

**KARMA YOGA IN ACTION**  
One who performs his duty without attachment, **surrendering the results unto the Supreme Lord**, is unaffected by sinful action, as the lotus leaf is untouched by water.(5.10)

The steadily devoted soul attains unadulterated peace because he **offers the result of all activities** **to Me**; whereas a person who is not in union with the Divine, who is greedy for the fruits of his labour, becomes entangled.(5.12)

\-\>We should be **careful that while offering the results of the activities to God** one should not have the **sense of proprietorship.**

* In fact all actions are being performed by the modes of Prakæti (Primordial Matter or the three modes of material nature). The fool, whose mind is deluded by egoism([*ahankāra-vimūḍha-ātmā*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/ahankara-vimudha-atma)), thinks: I am the doer.(3.27)

**THERE IS NOTHING CALLED FATE\!** 

* **God determines neither the doership nor the doings of men, nor even their contact with the fruit of actions; but it is Nature(modes of material nature (*guṇas*)) alone that functions. (5.14)**  
  **\-\>** Had He been our director, there would be no need for elaborate instructions on good and bad actions.   
  \-\>God is not responsible for our getting stuck with the sense of doership.  If He had deliberately created the pride of doing in us, then again we could have blamed Him for our misdoings.  But the fact is that the soul brings this pride onto itself out of ignorance.  If the soul chooses to do away with the ignorance, then God helps dispel it with His grace.   
  \-\> Thus, renunciation of the sense of doership is the responsibility of the soul.  The body is constituted of the three modes of material nature, and all actions are performed by the modes.  But out of ignorance, the soul identifies with the body and becomes implicated as the doer of actions, which are in fact done by material nature (verse 3.27).  
* The omnipresent God does not partake in the virtue or sin of anyone. Knowledge is enveloped by ignorance; hence it is that beings are constantly falling a prey to delusion. (15)

\-\>Similarly sometimes we **renounce things**, but we should not allow ourselves to have a sense of proprietorship.

* *Bhakti-rasāmṛta-sindhu* (1.2.258) by Śrīla Rūpa Gosvāmī“When persons eager to achieve liberation renounce things related to the Supreme Personality of Godhead, thinking them to be material, their renunciation is called incomplete.” **Renunciation is complete when it is in the knowledge that everything in existence belongs to the Lord and that no one should claim proprietorship over anything.** One should understand that, factually, nothing belongs to anyone. Then where is the question of renunciation? One who knows that everything is Kṛṣṇa’s property is always situated in renunciation. Since everything belongs to Kṛṣṇa, everything should be employed in the service of Kṛṣṇa. This perfect form of action in Kṛṣṇa consciousness is far better than any amount of artificial renunciation by a *sannyāsī* of the Māyāvādī school.

**TREAT EVERYONE EQUAL(ANIMALS, HUMANS OF DIFFERENT CAST/RACE/CREED) .**  
The humble sages, by virtue of true knowledge, see with equal vision a learned and gentle brāhmaṇa, a cow, an elephant, a dog and a dog-eater \[outcaste\].(5.18)

Those whose minds are established in **sameness and equanimity** have already conquered the conditions of birth and death. They are flawless like Brahman, and thus they are already situated in Brahman.(5.19)

**ACCEPTING KRISHNA AS GOD**  
A person in full consciousness of Me, knowing Me to be the ultimate beneficiary of all sacrifices and austerities, the Supreme Lord of all planets and demigods, and the benefactor and well-wisher of all living entities, attains peace from the pangs of material miseries.(5.29)

## **Chapter 6**

Krishna, by discussing ashtanga-yoga, establishes it as an impractical path; and therefore one should reject it in favour of bhakti-yoga. Ashtanga-yoga was mentioned in Text 5.27, to set a scene for Chapter 6\.  
**DEFINITION OF A SANYASI AND/OR REAL YOGI**  
**(KARMA YOG IS BETTER THAN RENUNCIATION)**  
The Supreme Personality of Godhead said: One **who is unattached to the fruits of his work(anāśhritaḥ karma-phalam)** and who works as he is obligated is in the renounced order of life, and he is the true mystic, not he who lights no fire and performs no duty.(6.1)

What is known as sanyās is non-different from Yog, for none become yogis without renouncing worldly desires.(6.2)

To the soul who is aspiring for perfection in Yog, work without attachment is said to be the means; to the sage who is already elevated in Yog, tranquility in meditation is said to be the means.(6.3)

→ A Krishna conscious person has no desires for self-satisfaction. His criterion of success is the satisfaction of Krsna, and thus he is the perfect sanyasi or perfect yogi.

(a) Karma-yoga is better than ashtanga-yoga because  
**Ashtanga-yoga, as a means to control the mind and senses is very difficult especially in this age.**  
Everyone in this world is working for personal self-interest (personal or extended).   
Sannyasis and mystic yogis are also self interested as follows:  
o Sannyasis – They are always seeking oneness with impersonal Brahman (desiring   
liberation) and they cease to perform their prescribed duties like ‘agnihotra yajnas’  
etc.  
o Mystic yogis – They also seek some satisfaction for their personal self by aspiring for   
mystic perfections (siddhis).  
**But the criteria of perfection is “to act in Krishna consciousness and not with a view to enjoy the fruits of one’s work”.**  
o Analogy: Limbs as part and parcel of the whole are supposed to serve the whole –  
Similarly Krishna consciousness is the duty of all living entities  
**(b) Therefore definition of ‘perfect sannyasi’ and ‘perfect yogi’ – Those who work only for the satisfaction of Krishna without any self-interest**  
Conclusion: Krishna conscious devotee is the most perfect and true sannyasi and yogi

---

What is called renunciation you should know to be the same as yoga, or linking oneself with the Supreme, O son of Pāṇḍu, for one can never become a yogī unless he **renounces the desire([*saṅkalpaḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/sankalpah)) (for sense gratification**.)(6.2)

* Detached action is the same as renunciation because both require freedom from desire of sense gratification. You are not supposed to be attached to inaction.  
* Stage of complete knowledge – When living entity ceases all sense-gratification activities and acts according to spiritual constitution.

  → How Yogis achieve this stage – Yogis practise this stage by restraining senses from material attachment.

  → How devotees achieve this stage – He has no opportunity to engage senses in anything other than Krishna; which implies, he is in a stage of complete knowledge ▪ Therefore Krishna conscious person is a perfect sannyasi and yogi ▪ Therefore bhakti includes the purpose of jnana (knowledge) and yoga (controlling senses).

---

A person is said to be elevated in yoga when, having renounced all material desires([*sarva-saṅkalpa*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/sarva-sankalpa)*\-sannyāsī*), he neither acts for sense gratification([*indriya-artheṣhu*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/indriya-artheshu)) nor engages in fruitive activities([*karmasu*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/karmasu)). (6.4)  
→Here ‘act of sense gratification’ and ‘fruitive activities’ should not be confused with ‘prescribed duty’. In 6.1 and 8.7 Krishna has already cleared that Karma Yog is better than renunciation. Hence you should keep in mind that you should not perform your prescribed duty only for the reason of sense gratification.

→ Krishna conscious person can do everything for Krishna’s satisfaction and thus perfectly detach from fruitive activities.  
---

**WE HAVE TO DO IT OURSELVES(Controlling mind)**  
One must deliver himself with the help of his mind, and not degrade himself. The mind is the friend of the conditioned soul, and his enemy as well.(6.5)  
Oneís own self is the friend of the soul by whom the lower self (consisting of the mind, senses and body) has been conquered; even so, the very self of him, who has not conquered his lower self, behaves antagonistically like an enemy. (6.6)  
**HOW A PERFECT YOGI TREATS HIS ENEMIES**  
He who looks upon well-wishers and neutrals as well as mediators, friends and foes, relatives and inimicals, the virtuous and the sinful with equanimity, stands supreme. (6.9)  
**ALL ACTIVITIES OF A YOGI(HE REMAINS ALOOF)**  
A transcendentalist should always engage his body, mind and self in relationship with the Supreme([*yuñjīta*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/yunjita)); he should live alone ([*rahasi*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/rahasi)) in a secluded place and should always carefully control his mind([*yata-chitta-ātmā*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/yata-chitta-atma)). He should be free from desires([*nirāśhīḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/nirashih)) and feelings of possessiveness([*aparigrahaḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/aparigrahah)).(6.10)  
**ABOUT EATING, SLEEPING AND RECREATION**  
There is no possibility of one becoming a yogī, O Arjuna, if one eats too much or eats too little, sleeps too much or does not sleep enough.(6.16)  
He who is regulated/moderate([*yukta*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/yukta)) in his habits of **eating([*āhāra*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/ahara))**, **sleeping([*svapna-avabodhasya*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/svapna-avabodhasya))**, **recreation([*vihārasya*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/viharasya))** and **work([*yukta cheṣhṭasya karmasu*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/yukta%20cheshtasya%20karmasu)/balance of work)** can mitigate all material pains by practising the yoga system.(6.17)  
**UNWAVERING**  
As a flame does not flicker in a windless place, such is stated to be the picture of the disciplined mind of the Yog∂ practising meditation on God. (6.19)  
One should engage oneself in the practice of yoga with determination and faith and not be deviated from the path. One should abandon, without exception, all material desires born of mental speculation and thus control all the senses on all sides by the mind.(6.24)  
**PRACTICE**  
From wherever the mind wanders due to its flickering and unsteady nature, one must certainly withdraw it and bring it back under the control of the Self. (6.26)  
**KRISHNA EVERYWHERE( (Ref. Bg. 18.61 “ishvara sarva...”)**  
A true yogī observes Me(Supersoul) in all beings and also sees every being in Me. Indeed, the self-realised person sees Me, the same Supreme Lord, everywhere.(6.29)  
He who sees Me (the Universal Self) present in all beings, and all beings existing within Me, he is never lost to me, nor am I ever lost to him. (6.30)  
**ARJUNA’S QUERY ABOUT MIND & SOLUTION PROVIDED BY KRISHNA**  
Arjuna said: O Madhusūdana, the system of yoga which You have summarized appears impractical and unendurable to me, for the mind is restless and unsteady.(6.33)  
The mind is restless, turbulent, obstinate and very strong, O Kṛṣṇa, and to subdue it, I think, is more difficult than controlling the wind.(6.34)  
Lord Śrī Kṛṣṇa said: O mighty-armed son of Kuntī, it is undoubtedly very difficult to curb the restless mind, but it is possible by suitable practice and by detachment.(6.35)  
**WHAT HAPPENS TO THOSE WHO FAIL PERFECTION IN YOGA DUE TO WORLDLY ATTACHMENTS**  
Arjuna said: O Kṛṣṇa, what is the destination of the unsuccessful transcendentalist, who in the beginning takes to the process of self-realisation with faith but who later desists due to worldly-mindedness and thus does not attain perfection in mysticism?(6.37)  
The Supreme Personality of Godhead said: Son of Pṛthā, a transcendentalist engaged in auspicious activities does not meet with destruction either in this world or in the spiritual world; one who does good, My friend, is never overcome by evil.(6.40)  
The unsuccessful yogī, after many, many years of enjoyment on the planets of the pious living entities, is born into a family of righteous people, or into a family of rich aristocracy.(6.41)  
Or \[if unsuccessful after long practice of yoga\] he takes his birth in a family of transcendentalists who are surely great in wisdom. Certainly, such a birth is rare in this world.(6.42)  
On taking such a birth, he revives the divine consciousness of his previous life, and he again tries to make further progress in order to achieve complete success, O son of Kuru.(6.43)  
By virtue of the divine consciousness of his previous life, he automatically becomes attracted to the yogic principles – even without seeking them. Such an inquisitive transcendentalist stands always above the ritualistic principles of the scriptures(6.44).  
And when the yogī engages himself with sincere endeavour in making further progress, being washed of all contaminations, then ultimately, **achieving perfection after many, many births of practice**, he attains the supreme goal.(6.45)

**WHO IS SUPERIOR TO ALL  ACCORDING TO KRISHNA**  
A yogī is greater than the ascetic, greater than the empiricist and greater than the fruitive worker. Therefore, O Arjuna, in all circumstances, be a yogī.(4.46)  
And of all yogīs, the one with **great faith ([*śhraddhā-vān*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/shraddha-van))** who **always abides in Me**, **thinks of Me within himself([*mat-gatena*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/mat-gatena))** and **renders transcendental loving service to Me** ([*bhajate*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/bhajate)) – he is the most intimately united with Me in yoga and is **the highest of all(or He is considered to be the BEST OF ALL YOGIS)**([*yukta-tamaḥ*](https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/w/yukta-tamah)). That is My opinion.(4.47)
